mile wide and an inch deep.

00:33:12.440 --> 00:33:17.900
And it's sort of like
you start to learn

00:33:17.900 --> 00:33:21.252
what the best batteries are
being made of these days.

00:33:21.252 --> 00:33:22.990
[FF] A little bit
about tons of stuff.

00:33:22.990 --> 00:33:24.040
[CD] A lot of stuff.

00:33:24.040 --> 00:33:27.105
But I agree with you,
it really does help me

00:33:27.105 --> 00:33:29.136
to understand the science more.

00:33:29.136 --> 00:33:29.802
[FF] Absolutely.

00:33:29.802 --> 00:33:35.320
And that's why we are hopefully
encouraging researchers

00:33:35.320 --> 00:33:39.630
to think about
presenting your science.

00:33:39.630 --> 00:33:44.270
Because the very nature of
thinking about the presentation

00:33:44.270 --> 00:33:48.090
clarifies what you are
trying to communicate.

00:33:48.090 --> 00:33:51.792
It's a very, very important
part of their education.

00:33:51.792 --> 00:33:53.500
